So much must suffice for this topic. For, in its essence, it has been made so clear, that in deter- mining a question of duty it is not difficult to see which duty is to be preferred to any other. Moreoverâ even in the social relations themselves there are gradations of duty so well defined that it can easily be seen which duty takes prece- dence of any other: our first duty is to the immor-tal gods3 our second, to country3 our third, to parentsÍ¾ and so on, in a descending scale, to the rest.

From this brief discussion, then, it can be under- stood that people are often in doubt not only whether an action is morally right or wrong, but also, when a choice is offered between two moral actions, which one is morally better. This point, as I remarked above, has been overlooked by Panaetius. But let us now nass on to what remains.
